<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38220d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38220d">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38220d"> 220(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> epidemic / endemic / sporadic</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Syphilis also, which at the end of the XVth century began to infect Europe, is ignored by The Nights. I do not say it actually began: diseases do not begin except with the dawn of humanity; and their history, as far as we know, is simple enough. They are at first sporadic and comparatively non-lethal: at certain epochs which we can determine, and for reasons which as yet we cannot, they break out into <mark>epidemics</mark> raging with frightful violence: they then subside into the <mark>endemic</mark> state and lastly they return to the milder <mark>sporadic</mark> form <font color="green">[this is followed by examples of the spread of &ldquo;English cholera,&rdquo; the &ldquo;Greater Pox,&rdquo; gonorrhea, pest, syphilis and the Aleppo &ldquo;button&rdquo;]</font>. <small> Richard F. Burton, &ldquo;Terminal Essay&rdquo;, <a name="RBTE1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE1"><cite title="source">The Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) X, 88</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
